# üêû bug report

### Affected Package
The issue is caused by package @angular/router

### Is this a regression?
I have not tested it on older versions of Angular. I'm currently using Angular 9.

### Description

I'm building an application that sets up a couple of values that I would like to keep in query params for users to easily share.

I tried to find a good solution on how to properly manage and keep them in sync with values set in services, but it seems that there aren't many solutions available, so I came up with custom one.

I came up with service that hides implementation details from consumers, so they do not know that additional data handling is done, so they can use these values as normal:

```
export class ValueService {
  private value: number;
  private valueSource: BehaviorSubject<number>;
  value$: Observable<number>;

  constructor(private route: ActivatedRoute, private router: Router) {
    const valueParam = this.route.snapshot.queryParams?.value;

    if (valueParam) {
      this.value = valueParam;
    } else {
      this.value = 5;
      this.router.navigate([window.location.pathname], {
        queryParamsHandling: 'merge',
        queryParams: { value: this.value },
        replaceUrl: true,
      })
    }

    this.valueSource = new BehaviorSubject<number>(this.value);
    this.value$ = this.valueSource.asObservable();
  }

updateValue(value: number) {
    this.valueSource.next(value);
    this.value = value;
    this.router.navigate([window.location.pathname], {
      queryParamsHandling: 'merge',
      queryParams: { value: this.value },
    })
  }

  getValue(): number {
    return this.value;
  }
}
```

Main problem with this solution is that when I use multiple services with similar implementation, only one value is set in query params and other seem to be cancelled out.

E.g. I have ```value = 5``` and ```value2 = 7```. In query params my output will be ?value=5 and not ```?value=5&value=7```

I was able to fix it by wrapping ```this.router.navigate()``` with ```setTimeout()``, but I don't think it is a good solution for the long run.

I think that the problem is that they all fire at the same time instead of sequentially, which causes one of them to be cancelled. I have not found solution to fix this issue. I suspect this may be a bug in Angular.

