### Description
I think it could be helpful to type SimpleChanges. I was thinking about doing the necessary changes to the repo and create a PR. I've created the issue so you guys can give me feedback if I can and should do this or if it is better to me to find something else to do. I like Angular and I want to start contributing.


### Current interface:
```ts
export class SimpleChange {
  constructor(public previousValue: any, public currentValue: any, public firstChange: boolean) {}

  isFirstChange(): boolean {
    return this.firstChange;
  }
}

export interface SimpleChanges {
  [propName: string]: SimpleChange;
}
```

### Proposed interface:
```ts
export class SimpleChange<T> {
  constructor(public previousValue: T, public currentValue: T, public firstChange: boolean) {}

  isFirstChange(): boolean {
    return this.firstChange;
  }
}

export type SimpleChanges<T> = { [P in keyof T]?: { previousValue?: T[P], currentValue: T[P] }; }
```

# üöÄ Feature request
Following this [PR](https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/pull/15819) it is now possible to extend build configuration.
Could it not possible to extends `serve` as well ? Additionnallly, `ng serve ` always searches for entries under ng-serve. Could it not be possible that if those entries are not present it uses values directly under `build` ?
### Description
 if we suppose that we have 2 build environment and 3 localize entries, we will need 6 entries under `serve` to test it locally.
```js
{
  "configurations": {
    "production": {
      "fileReplacements": [
        {
          "replace": "src/environments/environment.ts",
          "with": "src/environments/environment.prod.ts"
        }
      ]
    },
    "production2": {
      "fileReplacements": [
        {
          "replace": "src/environments/environment.ts",
          "with": "src/environments/environment.prod2.ts"
        }
      ]
    },
    "li18n1": {},
    "li18n2": {},
    "li18n3": {}
  }
}
```
If we are to use all these configs values under serve, we will need 6 entries. I wonder if it cannot be possible to run ng serve -c="i18n1, production1" and to directly use both configs

#### Feature Description

When creating a new theme object we are able to control part but not all colors. 
e.g. $dark-dividers which are part of a $foreground map are not customizable by default and needs a little workaround to actually make changes to it.

with sass new module system this can be achieved way more declaratively and easily, but variable such as $dark-dividers will need a _!default_ attribute

#### Use Case

// _theming.proxy.scss
```
@forward "~@angular/material/theming" with (
  $dark-dividers: #979797
);
```

will apply the new color to dividers and provide a better customization options.

For backwards compatibility, we do not want to generate density
styles multiple times. With the new API, the theme mixins include
density styles by default and this could mean that common theme setup as
followed could result in duplicate density styles:

```scss
@include angular-material-theme($light-theme);

.dark-theme {
  @include angular-material-theme($dark-theme);
}
```

Ideally, developers would now use the `angular-material-color` mixin for
their dark theme styles (as recommended in the theming guide), but we
cannot expect this to happen for all applications immediately, so we
provide code in Angular Material that automatically ensures that the
default density styles are not generated a second time.

**Note**: We will still warn if the same color or typography configuration
is generated. Also we will still warn if explicit density configurations
are generated multiple times.
